				<div class="c-issue-toc__article-collapse-inner">
					<p>The article is devoted to the work and thought of Jan Gwalbert Pawlikowski (1860-1939), one of the first Polish thinkers, who wrote about the need to protect landscape. Through analyzing a number of Pawlikowski's texts and manifestos (including the essay <em>Culture and nature </em>from 1913), the author is able to examine Pawlikowski's "philosophy of landscape," which constituted an important part of this thinking about nature protection. Pawlikowski's theory is also compared to contemporary philosophical texts about landscape aesthetics (a.o. A. Berque, A. Carlson, P. d’Angelo, A. Roger).</p>
